<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06176182 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06176182 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Levy  </CAPTION><LEADPARA>  Israeli government officials Sunday rejected stated U.S. intentions to link$10 billion in loan guarantees vital for new Soviet immigration to a freeze onsettlements in the occupied territories of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.Ministers of Yitzhak Shamir's conservative government, which supportsexpansion of Israeli settlements in the occupied territories, said they wouldattempt to persuade the United States that the two issues should be treatedseparately. &quot;We are doing everything so this linkage will not be made,&quot;Foreign Minister David Levy said, after Sunday's weekly Cabinet meeting here.;   The ministers spoke after Zalman Shoval, Israeli ambassador to Washington,said Israel would be forced to choose between the loan guarantees fromWashington and expanding settlements in the territories. Shoval made hiscomments on the Voice of Israel radio Saturday. Shamir's office immediatelydistanced itself from the ambassador's statements.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ISRAELI OFFICIALS REJECT U.S. LOAN REQUIREMENTS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign news in brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  From Mercury News wire services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910624  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  148  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday June 24, 199100176182,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>